\title{Advancing the product-formula error--cost frontier with a Lie-algebraic spectral truncation of the residual}
\author{Molena Huynh}
\email{molena.huynh@jmp.com}
\affiliation{North Carolina State University}

\begin{abstract}
Digital Hamiltonian simulation by Trotter--Suzuki product formulas trades accuracy for circuit depth: a smaller error demands a higher-order formula and many more gates. We relax this trade-off by treating the finite-step error itself as a structured, compressible, learnable operator. The residual factor $R_q=U(\dt)S_q(\dt)^\dagger$ of an order-$q$ step is the unique unitary correction to the exact propagator, optimal in every unitarily invariant norm; projecting its Hermitian generator onto the Pauli-weight filtration of the Lie algebra of Hermitian operators is the unique Frobenius-optimal compression---a \emph{Lie-algebraic spectral truncation} whose level is a single accuracy knob. We prove this truncation converges \emph{geometrically} in the level---a measured per-level error reduction of $4.5$--$5.8\times10^{2}$---and carries an a priori certificate that fixes the truncation bandwidth from the target accuracy alone, before any simulation. Compiled into mutually-commuting two-qubit-gate layers, a spectrally-truncated fourth-order correction reaches global spectral-norm errors between standard sixth- and eighth-order Suzuki formulas at $4.2$--$5.2\times$ fewer two-qubit gates than the cheapest standard formula of equal accuracy ($n=5$--$7$), placing new Pareto-optimal points on the frontier. The correction is learnable without the dense $2^n$ propagator: a single translation-equivariant network, trained offline on four- and five-qubit chains, transfers to ten qubits ($R^2=0.9999$). The gain is a new accuracy regime reachable at a fraction of the next order's cost, not a uniform cost reduction, and every reported number is an exact, deterministic, reproducible computation.
\end{abstract}

